==Old English==

===Spellings===
burh, burg

===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*burg-'', from Indo-European ''*bhərgh-'' ‘fortified elevation’.  Cognate with Old Frisian [[burch]], Old Saxon [[burg]] (Dutch [[burcht]]), Old High German [[burg]] (German [[Burg]] ‘castle’), Old Norse [[borg]] (Swedish [[borg]]), Gothic [[𐌱𐌰𐌿𐍂𐌲𐍃]] ‘town’.  The IE root is also the source of Celtic ''*brig-'' (Middle Irish ''brī'' ‘hill’, Welsh [[bera]] ‘stack’), Avestan ''brzant-'' ‘high’, Greek [[πύργος]] ‘tower’.

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /burh/

===Noun===
'''burh''' ''f'' (''pl'' '''byriġ''')
# a [[stronghold]] or [[fort]]
# a [[dwelling]]-place
# a [[town]] or [[city]]

